+{"id":"br-r41-c1-01","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] all_pairs_node_connectivity over-reported on directed graphs","description":"fnx's all_pairs_node_connectivity dispatches to _fnx.all_pairs_node_connectivity_rust, whose directed-graph path over-counts internally-node-disjoint paths. Reproducer: DiGraph on edges [(0,1),(1,2),(2,3),(3,0),(0,2)] — nx.local_node_connectivity(G, 3, 0) correctly returns 1 (only one internally-disjoint path), but the bulk Rust helper put {0:2, 1:2, 2:2} for source 3 (and symmetric overcounts for every source-target pair in this graph). Fixed by delegating the directed branch to networkx; the undirected Rust fast path is retained for Graph / MultiGraph.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","close_reason":"Fixed: directed inputs delegate to nx.all_pairs_node_connectivity; undirected + multigraph paths still use the Rust helper. Verified that DiGraph, undirected karate_club_graph, and a 4-node MultiGraph all match nx exactly."}
+{"id":"br-r41-c2-01","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] voterank used wrong tie-break order → divergent ranking after top few","description":"fnx.voterank delegated to _raw_voterank, whose Rust tie-break ordered ties by a different criterion than networkx. nx uses `max(G.nodes, key=score)` which returns the first-iterated max — on karate_club_graph that means the lowest-labelled tied node wins. Concrete diff: nx returns [33, 0, 32, 2, 1, 5, 31, 23, 6, 3, 24, 29, 4, 8]; fnx returned [33, 0, 32, 2, 1, 31, 5, 23, 6, 3, 24, 29, 10, 8] — positions 5/6 and position 12 differ. Rewrote the Python wrapper over nx's literal algorithm (G.nodes iteration order with max()). Verified: karate full & top5, directed example, single node, empty all match nx exactly.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","close_reason":"Fixed: voterank now implements nx's algorithm directly so ties break by node iteration order. All known test cases match nx output verbatim."}
+{"id":"br-r41-c3-01","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] dispersion used wrong neighbour-check AND wrong normalisation formula","description":"Two bugs in fnx._dispersion_pair, caught by a karate_club_graph probe (u=0, v=4 returned 0.5 in fnx but 0.0 in nx):

1. Shared-neighbour check: fnx computed `shared_in_common = (s_nbrs & t_nbrs) & common` — restricting the shared neighbour of candidate pair (s, t) to the set of u-and-v common neighbours. nx only requires the shared neighbour to be a neighbour of u: `nbrs_s = u_nbrs ∩ G[s] - {u,v}` then `nbrs_s.isdisjoint(G[t])`. The fnx restriction was too tight, so pairs (s, t) that nx would exclude — because they share a neighbour-of-u that isn't a common neighbour of {u, v} — got counted, inflating dispersion scores.

2. Normalisation: fnx used `(disp + b) / (embeddedness + c) ** alpha` (alpha on denominator), nx uses `(disp + b) ** alpha / (embeddedness + c)` (alpha on numerator). Equivalent only when alpha=1.

Rewrote _dispersion_pair to match nx's Backstrom-Kleinberg algorithm verbatim. Verified full-graph, u=0 vector, single pair, alpha=2, b/c params, and unnormalized all match nx.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","close_reason":"Fixed. _dispersion_pair is now a literal port of nx's algorithm. All probes on karate_club_graph (dict, u=0, single pair, alpha=2, b/c, normalized=False) match nx exactly."}
